ETF Portfolio Analysis

Portfolios

Low Risk Portfolio

The aim of the low risk portfolio is to maintain an acceptable return while exposing investors to lower risk levels. The minimum variance portfolio was used to decide the weights of this portfolio.

Medium Risk Portfolio

The aim for the medium risk portfolio is to generate a higher return by taking on a reasonable level of risk; balancing return on risk. The tangent portfolio was used to decide the weights of this portfolio.

High Risk Portfolio

The aim for the high risk portfolio is to maximise returns. This can result in a higher level of risk, but greater returns are generated. For the weights of the portfolio, we decided to rebalance asset allocation. Bond ETFs have lower expected returns^, so we decided to not allocate to bond ETFs, and allocate more to riskier assets, in order to maximise returns while maintaining a decent Sharpe ratio.

Backtesting Against Market

Through backtesting on past data (2001 - 2022), the results are as shown:

  • Initial investment of 10,000 JPY
  • Market performance (38004.90 JPY)
  • High risk portfolio outperforms the market (65615.91 JPY)
  • Medium risk portfolio outperforms the market (49197.78 JPY)
  • Low risk portfolio under-performs the market (28613.10 JPY)

Correlation Plot

The correlation plot is used to visually identify the stocks that are highly correlated. One advantage of having low correlation between assets is a reduction of volatility of the portfolio.

Observations:

  • All equities have a positive correlation with one another.
  • Japanese Equities (1306.JT, 1343.JT) are weakly correlated to US equities.
  • There are two distinct groups of equities that are strongly correlated.
